Last week, at a meeting of Ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as a second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has been actively involved in a number of Agency projects over the years.
But the way to space Poland began much earlier.
Before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space voyages, but this was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who presented ideas in Warsaw's astronomical observatory on 6 December 1933 from his innovative work "Introduction into space".
The ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after a few years Sterfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Luis Hirsch Award for "Introduction into space".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 66), mentioned earlier, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and space science.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-famous space propagandist, and his contribution was assessed, including the fact that one of the craters on the other side of the Moon was named in his honour.
By 1925, a railway train equipped with a rocket engine had already been built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown as well as the details of the project.
It is not clear even that a rocket was to be used to launch or brake the trolley.
The information on this cloth is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery has begun to think about missiles.
The study was carried out by the Arms Technology Section in cooperation with Professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzicki.
It is evident from the retained evidence that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, a specialized press had the idea of a photoelectric surveyor rocket proposed by an engineer named Rogozinski, and the following year the work of “Aircraft torpedo and air bomb rocket” was published by the author of Llivy-Kivobločka.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, the interim scientific advisory committee (Temporary Advisory and Scientific Advisory Committee), which coordinated all the work, was involved in all military-use projects.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work, the work ended because of the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautic Society (Polish Astronautic Society).
For the first time, society is mentioned in November 1954, issue of The Problem, which publishes four volumes of articles on astronauts.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovic offered to organize a society that would engage in space.
At the time, artificial satellite projects had already been built into circulation, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since early 1956, the Polish Astronautics Society (POA) has attempted to join the international Astronautics Federation (based in 1951) and has already become a valid member of the PIA in autumn.
And next year, the first President of the PIA, Kazimez Zarankevich (1902-1959), became Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his very death, which occurred in 1959.
Since 1956, PIA has made a significant contribution to the development of a very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologicala), which has become the first Polish rocket to carry out a scientific study.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, capable of overcoming 1,800 metres, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
An improved version of RM-1A was subsequently constructed, and in the summer of 1959 two-step RM-2 rocket tests were conducted in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was about 1.4 metres long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do the actual scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could have overrun 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high wind.
But further development was suspended in 1962.
The first RM rockets were inherited by Meteor-1, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (identified as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed and differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
Meteor-1A had a space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B was 0.34 litres, and Meteor-1C was 0.62l.
The maximum flight range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, a meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute and its first summer tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket, with a starting weight of 380 kg, was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
The meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland ' s accession to COSPAR (the Space Research Committee) in 1960 and the establishment of a national committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaschevski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
