Sabo: "Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
In the view of Stephen Sabo, the US-Europe liaison expert, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first realized that it would vote against the Palestinians' request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli action in Gaza.
Germany must now be careful about its special relations with Israel.
At the same time, I believe that the American position is not supported either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being overly critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
As a result, NATO has implemented this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, from a policy that the United States has been governed by, so to speak, to a German foreign policy.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the lack of an agreed common policy among Europeans.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're just playing their part, but they're on their way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
This is the foreign policy that France or Britain is pursuing.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position in their national interest independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, i.e. exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests differ greatly from those of other major States, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the United Nations?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Persian Gulf States.
It therefore needs to be cautious not to offend the public and the elite in the Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its part.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to it, it's not a completely unilateral connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Did Germany harm its relations with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
This signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be considered.
In Europe, there are differing views on the Palestinian initiative.
On the contrary, it was clear to the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European States?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama Government has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But in the light of the local political situation, the Government cannot, of course, take this position openly.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not as significant as it always seems.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all thrilled by Netanyahu's policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of a vital partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a single, non-contrary European policy, but that is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot act as part of a broader approach and must instead act on their own vision of the situation.
That's what they do with the euro.
In the future, I think Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
Clearly, it is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
The subject was always sensitive.
But I think the Germans clearly have a more independent role to play.
If Germany itself sees itself as an important international player, will it really play a major role?
Or is Germany still hard to lead?
Germany is not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany assumes an important role, there are a wide range of anti-German feelings.
The Germans are more than just coping with it.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It must take into account a wide range of neighbours and views, and this is not easy.
So, the U.S.'s influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at this point, the EU is not filling this vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a larger role.
Even if you don't like it, it's unpleasant, or it's not loving you, it's a life like this.
Stephen Sabo, Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., where academics and political experts from Europe and North America study together the problems of the transatlantic community.
