On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of the many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he said had to be transferred to a military prison.
During the cross-examination hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fein stated that the records of weekly visits to Manning's prison administration for nine months in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination in the defence motion for termination of Manning ' s case was conducted on the basis that the conditions of his detention were severe and were in themselves sufficient punishment the following day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of kidnapping several thousand secret documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that the source of the information was Manning.
During the Friday hearing, Prosecutor Fein, together with Manning, reviewed the reports that were filed after Manning's visits to the Administration during his stay at Quantico Prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During their visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he viewed the treatment of the prison administration as “superior” and the general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized”.
The reports considered do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, although Manning was directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Fein argues.
Manning replied that he had expressed his oral concern about these issues and that the representatives of his administration had discussed these problems with him and stated that they would, but had not fixed them in writing.
"They wrote down "no problems" (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't raise the subject in a conversation," says Manning.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Linde, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his mistreatment in January 2011 during a meeting of the commission that considered the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing several months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting, he wanted him to remove the regime of “injury prevention” and mitigate the conditions of detention.
The representatives of the military leadership explained that a limited detention regime, below the suicide prevention surveillance regime, had been introduced to protect the prisoner as well as to protect others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that everything is fine with me so that they can reverse the trauma prevention regime... so that my level of life will improve, in my opinion,” explained Manning.
On Thursday, Manning testified to his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that the thoughts of suicide had appeared to him in Kuwait and that he had lost consciousness because of the intense heat of one day.
He explained that it was psychologically difficult for you not to know how your participation was going and what was going on in the outside world.
"My world has fallen to Camp Arifjan, the size of my prison," Manning said on Thursday.
- I thought I was gonna die in this cage."
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 21 hours — and often more than 23 hours a day — alone.
Manning says he's only allowed to leave mattresses, blankets, hats, a few clothes and glasses.
He says that he tried to move because sleep or even just lie down during the daytime banned the rules.
